ctors in the first half of the twentieth century. Hydrotherapy, sterilization, electroshock, lobotomy, and clitoridectomy—these were among the drastic somatic treatments used in these hospitals.By allowing the would-be healers and those in psychological and physical distress to speak for themselves, Braslow captures the intense and emotional interplay surrounding these therapies. His investigation combines revealing clinical detail with the immediacy of "being there" in the institutional setting while decisions are made, procedures undertaken, and results observed by all those involved. We learn how well-intentioned physicians could rationalize and regard as therapeutic treatments that often had dreadful consequences, and how much the social and cultural world is inscribed within the practice of biological psychiatry. The book will interest historians of medicine, practicing psychiatrists, and everyone who knows or has seen what it's like to be in mental distress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEsprit et corps. 0aMaladies mentalesxPhysiothérapiexHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-Unis. 0aMaladies mentalesxTraitementxHistoirex20e sièclexÉtats-Unis. 0aMental illnessxPhysical therapyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMental illnessxPhysical therapyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMental illnessxTreatmentxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aMental illnessxTreatmentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMental illnessxTreatment. 0aMind and body. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  abiological psychiatry.  abrutal ways.  aclitoridectomy.  aelectroshock therapy.  ahydrotherapy.  alobotomy.  amadness.  amedical.  amental distress.  amental health care.  amental health history.  amental illness.  amental patients.  aneuroscience.  apatie